---
import ReportLayout from '../../../layouts/ReportLayout.astro';
import ReportSection from '../../../components/ReportSection.astro';
import ResultsTable from '../../../components/ResultsTable.astro';
import SkillTable from '../../../components/SkillTable.astro';
import CostTable from '../../../components/CostTable.astro';
import SkillGrid from '../../../components/SkillGrid.astro';

const models = ['Claude Opus 4.6', 'GPT-5.4', 'Gemini 3.1 Pro'];

const results = [
  { name: 'Claude Opus 4.6', avgScore: 0.825, passRate: '4/4', totalCost: '$1.03', avgTokens: '8,955' },
  { name: 'GPT-5.4', avgScore: 0.814, passRate: '4/4', totalCost: '$0.48', avgTokens: '6,042' },
  { name: 'Gemini 3.1 Pro', avgScore: 0.768, passRate: '3/4', totalCost: '$0.31', avgTokens: '4,009' },
];

const skills = [
  { name: 'Frontend Design', description: 'Responsive dashboard with animations, semantic HTML. Tests layout, component architecture, and CSS implementation.' },
  { name: 'MCP Server Builder', description: 'TypeScript MCP server with Zod schemas, auth, and pagination. Tests protocol compliance and type safety.' },
  { name: 'Skill Creator', description: 'Write a SKILL.md with frontmatter, examples, and edge cases. Tests structured documentation and specification writing.' },
  { name: 'Excel Generator', description: '3-year SaaS financial model with openpyxl and formulas. Tests numerical reasoning and spreadsheet architecture.' },
];

const skillScores = [
  { skill: 'Frontend Design', scores: [0.75, 0.75, 0.75] },
  { skill: 'MCP Server Builder', scores: [0.83, 0.79, 0.67] },
  { skill: 'Skill Creator', scores: [0.88, 0.92, 0.86] },
  { skill: 'Excel Generator', scores: [0.83, 0.79, 0.79] },
];

const costData = {
  headers: ['Inference Cost', 'Judge Cost', 'Total', 'Cost per Skill'],
  rows: [
    { name: 'Claude Opus 4.6', cells: ['$0.49', '$0.14', '$0.63', '$0.16'] },
    { name: 'GPT-5.4', cells: ['$0.17', '$0.14', '$0.31', '$0.08'] },
    { name: 'Gemini 3.1 Pro', cells: ['$0.12', '$0.14', '$0.26', '$0.06'] },
  ],
};

const setupModels = [
  { name: 'Claude Opus 4.6', provider: 'Anthropic', release: 'Current' },
  { name: 'GPT-5.4', provider: 'OpenAI', release: 'March 5, 2026' },
  { name: 'Gemini 3.1 Pro', provider: 'Google', release: 'Current' },
];

const toc = [
  { id: 'setup', label: 'The Setup' },
  { id: 'results', label: 'Results' },
  { id: 'what-we-learned', label: 'What We Learned' },
  { id: 'economics', label: 'The Economics' },
  { id: 'ensemble-judging', label: 'Ensemble Judging' },
  { id: 'what-this-means', label: 'What This Means' },
  { id: 'caveats', label: 'Caveats' },
];
---

<ReportLayout
  title="Frontier Model Showdown"
  subtitle="Claude Opus 4.6 vs GPT-5.4 vs Gemini 3.1 Pro"
  description="Three frontier models, four skills, ensemble judges. Claude Opus scored highest at 0.825. Gemini was cheapest at $0.31."
  department="Frontier Model Evals"
  date="2026-03-08"
  dateFormatted="March 8, 2026"
  slug="frontier-showdown"
  toc={toc}
  models={models}
  methodology="3 frontier models, 4 skills, 12 total runs. Each output scored by deterministic rules (60%) and ensemble LLM judge (40%) with median aggregation across all 3 frontier models. Pass threshold: 0.70. Total benchmark cost: $1.82. Scores reflect model capabilities as of March 8, 2026. Benchmarked with EvalRig."
  turanuUrl="https://www.turanu.ai/i-tested-anthropics-official-skills-on-all-three-frontier-models/"
>
  <Fragment slot="intro">
    <p class="report-lede">
      GPT-5.4 dropped yesterday. That means we now have fresh frontier models from all
      three major providers sitting side by side. So we did what any reasonable person
      would do: we built a testing rig and ran them head-to-head on real software
      engineering tasks.
    </p>
    <p class="report-context">
      This isn't a vibes-based comparison. Every model got the exact same prompts, was
      evaluated by the same deterministic rules, and was scored by an ensemble of all
      three frontier models acting as judges. No model grades its own homework unchecked.
    </p>
  </Fragment>

  <ReportSection id="setup" title="The Setup">
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Model</th><th>Provider</th><th>Release</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          {setupModels.map(m => (
            <tr><td class="model-name">{m.name}</td><td>{m.provider}</td><td>{m.release}</td></tr>
          ))}
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <SkillGrid skills={skills} />

    <p>
      We chose these four specifically because they cover the quadrants of software
      engineering work where AI agents are most likely to be deployed: generating code
      from specs, analyzing data under pressure, reasoning about systems with complex
      constraints, and reviewing code for correctness and security.
    </p>
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="results" title="Results">
    <ResultsTable results={results} />

    <p>
      Claude Opus scored highest but cost the most. Gemini was cheapest but missed the
      pass threshold on one skill. GPT-5.4 landed in the middle on both quality and cost.
    </p>

    <h3>Skill-by-Skill Breakdown</h3>
    <SkillTable models={models} skills={skillScores} />
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="what-we-learned" title="What We Learned">
    <h3>Frontend Design &mdash; dead heat at 0.75</h3>
    <p>
      All three models scored identically. Layout, semantic HTML, and responsive CSS
      are well within every frontier model's capability. The differentiation happens
      elsewhere.
    </p>

    <h3>MCP Server Builder &mdash; Claude leads</h3>
    <p>
      Claude scored 0.83 vs 0.79 (GPT) and 0.67 (Gemini). Protocol-specific tasks
      with Zod schemas and auth patterns favored Claude's structured output style.
      Gemini's lower score here contributed to its 3/4 pass rate.
    </p>

    <h3>Skill Creator &mdash; GPT-5.4 wins</h3>
    <p>
      GPT-5.4 scored highest at 0.92, ahead of Claude (0.88) and Gemini (0.86).
      Documentation and specification writing benefited from GPT's concise,
      well-organized output style.
    </p>

    <h3>Excel Generator &mdash; Claude leads again</h3>
    <p>
      Claude scored 0.83 while GPT and Gemini tied at 0.79. The financial modeling
      task required numerical reasoning and formula architecture where Claude's
      verbose, detail-oriented approach paid off.
    </p>
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="economics" title="The Economics">
    <CostTable headers={costData.headers} rows={costData.rows} highlightCheapest={2} />

    <p>
      Judge costs are nearly identical ($0.14 each) &mdash; because every model's output gets
      judged by all three models regardless. The inference cost is where the gap appears.
    </p>
    <p>
      Claude Opus costs 3.3x more than Gemini while scoring only 7% higher. GPT-5.4 sits
      in the middle on both cost and quality. Total benchmark cost: $1.82 for 12 model runs.
    </p>
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="ensemble-judging" title="Ensemble Judging: Do Models Agree?">
    <p>
      <strong>High agreement</strong> (spread &lt; 0.10): The judges closely agreed on
      incident-response across all models. Analytical reasoning tasks have more objective
      criteria &mdash; the timeline is either accurate or it isn't.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Moderate disagreement</strong> (spread 0.15&ndash;0.25): PR review showed
      the most divergence. Claude-as-judge consistently scored higher than GPT-as-judge,
      particularly on completeness.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Notable pattern</strong>: Claude-as-judge was the most generous scorer overall,
      while GPT-as-judge was the strictest. Gemini fell in the middle. This is why the median
      strategy matters &mdash; it prevents any one model's scoring tendencies from dominating.
    </p>
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="what-this-means" title="What This Means">
    <p>
      <strong>Best quality:</strong> Claude Opus 4.6 scored highest (0.825) with the most
      detailed, structured outputs. Its verbose style is a strength on MCP and Excel tasks
      where thoroughness matters. But it costs 3.3x more than Gemini.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Best value:</strong> Gemini 3.1 Pro at $0.31 total is the cheapest option.
      But it missed the pass threshold on MCP Server Builder (0.67), making it the only
      model that didn't pass all four skills.
    </p>
    <p>
      <strong>Middle ground:</strong> GPT-5.4 passed everything at 0.814 for $0.48.
      Won Skill Creator outright. Balanced cost and quality.
    </p>
    <p>
      The spread between first and third is 0.057 points. All three are production-viable
      for most tasks. The choice comes down to your constraints &mdash; budget, pass rate
      requirements, or preference for output style.
    </p>
  </ReportSection>

  <ReportSection id="caveats" title="Caveats">
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Single run per model per skill.</strong> Production benchmarks should average over multiple runs. We ran at temperature 0.0 for maximum reproducibility.</li>
      <li><strong>Software engineering only.</strong> Results may differ for creative writing, math, or other domains.</li>
      <li><strong>Truncation penalty.</strong> All models lost judge points on completeness due to output truncation on ambitious tasks.</li>
      <li><strong>Pricing is a snapshot.</strong> Model costs change. Rankings reflect March 2026 pricing.</li>
      <li><strong>Shared blind spots.</strong> All three models judging each other reduces individual bias but doesn't eliminate systematic blind spots they may share.</li>
    </ul>
  </ReportSection>
</ReportLayout>

<style>
  .report-lede {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    line-height: 1.6;
    color: var(--text);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .report-context {
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.6;
  }

  .table-wrap {
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
    overflow-x: auto;
  }

  .model-name {
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--text);
  }
</style>
